@node Prepare mysql
@chapter Prepare mysql

@pindex prepare mysql
@cindex prepare mysql

Enter the mysql client as user root.@*
You are now at the mysql client prompt which looks like this "mysql>"@*
Add a super user called "new_admin"@*
Change "new_admin" to a name you prefer.@*
The new super user will have access to mysql from 3 places:@*
1) localhost@*
2) 127.0.0.1@*
3) An IP address of your choice (optional)@*
The last item (number 3) is the IP address "MYSQL Administrator"
will be connecting from.@*
@*
Below, change "new_admin" to something you prefer.@*
At the mysql prompt, enter the following:
@example
GRANT ALL PRIVILEGES ON *.* TO 'new_admin'@'localhost' WITH GRANT OPTION;
GRANT ALL PRIVILEGES ON *.* TO 'new_admin'@'127.0.0.1' WITH GRANT OPTION;
GRANT ALL PRIVILEGES ON *.* TO 'new_admin'@'192.168.1.4' WITH GRANT OPTION;
@end example
@*
Below, change "new_password" to something you prefer.@*
At the mysql prompt, enter the following:
@example
SET PASSWORD FOR 'new_admin'@'localhost' = PASSWORD('new_password');
SET PASSWORD FOR 'new_admin'@'192.168.1.4' = PASSWORD('new_password');
SET PASSWORD FOR 'new_admin'@'127.0.0.1' = PASSWORD('new_password');
@end example
@*
View all user and host combinations in the mysql database.@*
At the mysql prompt, enter the following:
@example
SELECT User, Host FROM mysql.user;
@end example
@*
Remove no name user. At the mysql prompt, enter the following:
@example
DROP USER ''@'localhost';
@end example
@*
Remove all users in this way except "new_admin" users.@*
At the mysql prompt, enter the following:
@example
DROP USER 'root'@'localhost';
@end example
@*
The "new_admin" super user should be the only remaining user.@*
The next command should display 3 "new_admin" host combinations.@*
At the mysql prompt, enter the following:
@example
SELECT User, Host FROM mysql.user;
@end example
@*
View all existing databases.  At the mysql prompt, enter the following:
@example
SHOW DATABASES;
@end example
@*
Delete the test database.  At the mysql prompt, enter the following:
@example
DROP DATABASE test;
@end example
@*
Again view all existing databases.@*
"information_squema" and "mysql" should be the only remaining 
databases.@*
At the mysql prompt, enter the following:
@example
SHOW DATABASES;
@end example
@*
We're done with mysql. At the mysql prompt, enter the following:
@example
exit
@end example

